<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,259,1008]" box="[199,1119,367,393]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,268,367,393]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Mine.</emphasis>
The solitary larva forms blotch mine. Pupation takes place within the mine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,259,1008]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,403,429]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Puparium.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[345,512,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 104–111" captionStartId="40.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[164,1422,210,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-18@40.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURES 104–111. Figures 104–106: Cerodontha (Poemyza) muscina (Meigen); 104: mine in Lolium giganteum leaf; 105– 106: posterior segments of puparium; 105: lateral view; 106: posterior view. Figures 107–108: C. (Poemyza) phragmitidis Nowakowski, posterior segments of puparium; 107: lateral view; 108: posterior view. Figures 109–111: C. (Poemyza) pygmaea (Meigen); 109: mine in Lolium giganteum leaf; 110–111: posterior segments of puparium; 110: lateral view; 111: posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158625" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158625/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Figs. 107, 108</figureCitation>
) Black, glossy; 
<quantity box="[700,789,403,430]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5 mm</quantity>
long, with distinct segmentation; surface smooth except for narrow wrinkled spine bands. Both posterior spiracles are set on a single narrow and long conical protuberance directed posteriorly; black, spherical and entirely separate. The puparium viewed from the side and above and posterior spiracles viewed from above are depicted in 
<bibRefCitation author="Nowakowski, J. T." box="[733,960,511,537]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="1 - 327" refId="ref73871" refString="Nowakowski, J. T. (1973) Monographie der europaishen Arten der Gattung Cerodontha Rond. (Diptera, Agromyzidae). Annales Zoologici, 31 (1), 1 - 327." type="journal article" year="1973">Nowakowski (1973</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation box="[972,1071,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 221–235" captionStartId="75.[151,264,1781,1805]" captionTargetBox="[200,1390,198,1736]" captionTargetId="figure-15@75.[185,1403,181,1757]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="FIGURES 221–235. Figures 221–225: Phytomyza nowakowskiana Beiger; 221–222: mine in Symphytum cordatum leaf; 223: empty puparium viewed from the side; 224: posterior segments of puparium (posterior view); 225: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 226–230: P. pulmonaria Nowakowski, reared from Myosotis sparsiflora; 226: mine; 227: puparium in mine; 228: empty puparium viewed from the side; 229: posterior segments of puparium (posterior view); 230: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 231–235: P. pulmonaria Nowakowski, reared from Symphytum asperum; 231: mines; 232: puparia in mine; 233: empty puparium viewed from the side; 234: posterior segments of puparium (posterior view); 235: posterior spiracles (posterior view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158671" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158671/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Fig. 227</figureCitation>
). Anal plate strongly protruding above the surface of the puparium viewed from the side and directed posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,259,1008]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,549,583,609]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Cephalopharyngeal skeleton.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[566,665,583,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 431–438" captionStartId="110.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[159,1419,196,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-18@110.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="110" captionText="FIGURES 431–438. Figures 431–434: Cerodontha (Poemyza) muscina (Meigen); 431: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 432: frontal view of head; 433: head viewed from the side; 434: spermathecae. Figures 435–438: C. (P.) phragmitidis Nowakowski; 435: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 436: frontal view of head; 437: head viewed from the side; 438: spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158774" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158774/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Fig. 435</figureCitation>
) Right mouthhook larger than the left, with ventro-anterior portion sharply abducted. Each mouthhook bears two narrow and sharp accessory teeth. Intermediate sclerite narrow, slightly curved, 1.66× as long as maximum height of left mouthhook. The mouthhook, intermediate sclerite and anterior portion of the pharyngeal sclerite are strongly sclerotized, dorsal and ventral cornua much less so. Indentation index 79. See also in 
<bibRefCitation author="Nowakowski, J. T." box="[322,546,727,753]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="1 - 327" refId="ref73871" refString="Nowakowski, J. T. (1973) Monographie der europaishen Arten der Gattung Cerodontha Rond. (Diptera, Agromyzidae). Annales Zoologici, 31 (1), 1 - 327." type="journal article" year="1973">Nowakowski (1973</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation box="[556,654,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 185–193" captionStartId="66.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[161,1418,194,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-18@66.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="FIGURES 185–193. Figures 185–188: P. artemisivora Spencer; 185: mine with larva (indicated by arrow) in Artemisia vulgaris leaf; 186–187: posterior segments of puparium; 186: lateral view; 187: posterior view. 188: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 189–193: P. aurei Hering; 189: mines in Chaerophyllum aromaticum leaf; 190: puparium on lower leaf surface; 191–192: posterior segments of puparium; 191: lateral view; 192: posterior view. 193: posterior spiracles (posterior view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158663/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Fig. 189</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,259,1008]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,357,763,789]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Female head.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[372,534,763,789]" captionStart="FIGURES 431–438" captionStartId="110.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[159,1419,196,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-18@110.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="110" captionText="FIGURES 431–438. Figures 431–434: Cerodontha (Poemyza) muscina (Meigen); 431: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 432: frontal view of head; 433: head viewed from the side; 434: spermathecae. Figures 435–438: C. (P.) phragmitidis Nowakowski; 435: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 436: frontal view of head; 437: head viewed from the side; 438: spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158774" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158774/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Figs. 436, 437</figureCitation>
) Brown, with proboscis yellow; orbit distinctly projecting above eye in profile; 2 orb s, 4 fr s; lunule very high and dramatically narrow, reaching the level between the posterior fr s and the anterior orb s; pped of medium size, flattened ventrally; gena medially 0.17× as high as maximum height of eye.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,259,1008]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,403,871,897]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Female genitalia.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[418,514,871,897]" captionStart="FIGURES 431–438" captionStartId="110.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[159,1419,196,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-18@110.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="110" captionText="FIGURES 431–438. Figures 431–434: Cerodontha (Poemyza) muscina (Meigen); 431: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 432: frontal view of head; 433: head viewed from the side; 434: spermathecae. Figures 435–438: C. (P.) phragmitidis Nowakowski; 435: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 436: frontal view of head; 437: head viewed from the side; 438: spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158774" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158774/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Fig. 438</figureCitation>
) Spermathecae equal in size, dark brown, spherical, flattened basally and apically, without basal collar. Neck of spermatheca cylindrical, more sclerotized near spermathecal duct, as high as wide. Spermathecal duct distinctly sclerotized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1250,979,1008]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" type="distribution">
